In [[number theory]] and [[combinatorics]], a '''multipartition''' of a positive [[integer]] ''n'' is a way of writing ''n'' as a [[summation|sum]], each element of which is in turn a [[Partition (number theory)|partition]].  The concept is also found in the theory of [[Lie algebra]]s.

==r-component multipartitions==
An ''r''-component multipartition of an integer ''n'' is an ''r''-tuple of partitions λ<sup>(1)</sup>,...,λ<sup>(r)</sup> where each λ<sup>(''i'')</sup> is a partition of some ''a''<sub>''i''</sub> and the  ''a''<sub>''i''</sub> sum to ''n''.  The number of ''r''-component multipartitions of ''n'' is denoted ''P''<sub>''r''</sub>(''n'').  Congruences for the function ''P''<sub>''r''</sub>(''n'') have been studied by [[A. O. L. Atkin]].

